6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BingX calculates funding rates every 8 hours using traditional perpetual mechanics with mark price vs index price deviations. RabbitX updates funding rates hourly, providing more frequent arbitrage opportunities but requiring closer monitoring. BingX's longer intervals offer more predictable rate patterns, while RabbitX's hourly updates can capture short-term premium/discount movements more effectively. Both use similar interest rate components but RabbitX's decentralized nature means rates reflect pure market dynamics without centralized intervention."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"RabbitX provides more frequent opportunities with hourly funding updates versus BingX's 8-hour cycles. However, BingX offers better liquidity depth and more predictable rate patterns for larger position sizes."},{"question":"How do gas fees affect arbitrage profitability on each platform?","answer":"BingX has no gas fees as a CEX, while RabbitX eliminates gas costs through its Starknet architecture. Both platforms avoid the gas fee burden that affects mainnet DEXs, making small arbitrage trades viable."},{"question":"Which platform has better execution speed for funding rate strategies?","answer":"RabbitX offers faster execution through off-chain order matching and Starknet settlement. BingX provides reliable execution but may have slightly higher latency during high volatility periods due to centralized infrastructure."},{"question":"What are the risks of funding rate arbitrage on these platforms?","answer":"BingX carries counterparty risk as a CEX but offers insurance funds. RabbitX has smart contract risk and lower liquidity but eliminates centralized custody concerns. Both require careful position sizing due to different liquidity profiles."}]}]
